events.event_name: Release of France's January 2026 Official Reserve Assets
events.description: France reported its official reserve assets for January 2026, showing a record high of €409.26 billion.

facts.fact_text: France's official reserve assets reached a record high of €409.26 billion in January 2026.

evidences.evidence_text: France’s official reserve assets increased to €409.26 billion in January 2026, reaching a fresh record high, from €362.74 billion in December.

facts.fact_text: Gold reserves increased to €334.05 billion in January from €287.48 billion in December.

evidences.evidence_text: driven by increases in gold reserves (€334.05 billion vs €287.48 billion in December)

facts.fact_text: Foreign currency reserves rose to €30.55 billion in January.

evidences.evidence_text: and foreign currency reserves (€30.55 billion vs €30.36 billion)

facts.fact_text: Claims on the IMF and other reserve assets saw declines in January.

evidences.evidence_text: On the other hand, declines were seen in claims on the IMF (€38.20 billion vs €38.41 billion) and other reserve assets (€6.46 billion vs €6.49 billion).

claims.claim_text: The rise in total reserves was primarily driven by the increase in gold and foreign currency reserves.

evidences.evidence_text: This represents a rise of €46.52 billion, driven by increases in gold reserves (€334.05 billion vs €287.48 billion in December) and foreign currency reserves (€30.55 billion vs €30.36 billion).
